March 23 Update: 
We have a handful of important updates to bring you tonight. As a reminder, if you have a school specific question, you’re asked to reach out to the school directly. If you have questions related to COVID-19, you can email covid19@mansd.org. 
Here are tonight’s updates:
Remote Learning: We're receiving significant snowfall this evening, but at this time we will continue with remote learning plans for tomorrow We DO NOT need to call for a snow day as we are in remote learning at this time.
Please be patient with new bus routes: We experienced unexpected delays Monday in our first run with new bus routes. We apologize to any families who were left waiting for food or were unable to wait for the bus. We made some small changes to the new routes – you can find information on the routes at www.mansd.org. 
Impact of snow on food distribution: We are hopeful that we will be able to distribute food tomorrow as planned, but we are watching the snow carefully. We will send an update in the morning. For those going to the bus stops to pick up food, please be careful. And for those out on the roads, please continue to be extra cautious around the buses. 
Additional food pick-up location: As we mentioned Sunday evening, the YMCA of Downtown Manchester will be distributing grab-and-go dinners every evening from 4:30-5:30 p.m. Families will be able to pick up breakfast and lunch from the Teen Center entrance, 42 Stark Street, beginning tomorrow. Buses will be dropping off food at the end of the route, then the Y will distribute those meals. You can get an idea of when the buses will drop food off by viewing the routes at www.mansd.org. 
Clarification on learning packets: We are not distributing packets each week, so if you have already picked up a packet from the bus or your child’s school, you do not need to get another one. If you have not yet picked up a packet for your child, please contact your school to arrange a pickup. 
Email for elementary school students: Parents, in order to help elementary school teachers communicate more effectively with their students, the district has turned on email for all elementary school students. This is only temporary and once normal operations resume we will revert back to our previous policy. Your student’s email address is the same login that they are currently using for Google Drive and Clever. If you have questions about your child’s login, please contact your child’s teacher directly. 
*Translation Services are currently unavailable from our notification provider. 
 

Remote Learning Materials Distribution To Begin 
The Manchester School District will begin the delivery of physical Remote Learning Materials on Thursday, March 19th. While some Remote Learning Materials have been delivered electronically, the core elementary materials as well as paper copies of some secondary (6-12) materials will now be available. Families can also access the elementary materials on the district website at the links below. Remote Learning materials will also be available for our Special Education Students as well as our English Learners. The District is utilizing our busses to make materials deliveries for ALL students along bus routes at the same times and locations as the existing food delivery schedule; however, for those Special Education students that use specialized transportation their materials will be delivered by their private provider (i.e. STS).

DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":4221,"s":" All Manchester School District students can access physical remote learning materials and food by meeting the bus at their regular stop, or the stop nearest their home if they are not a bus rider. Families have been or will be contacted by their schools or teachers to provide information and support as we initiate remote learning. This contact may be in the form of a phone call, e-mail, Google Classroom or other electronic format. In the case of a phone call you may see a blocked caller ID. Please answer blocked caller IDs in case it is your child’s teacher calling. This family contact is one way we are recording student attendance. It is important to remember school is not cancelled, these are not “snow days.” 
To determine where and at what time the bus will be in your area please visit the Manchester School District Home Page. You will be directed to the list of bus routes associated with your child’s school. Select the route and stop closest to your home. Please be patient and allow for buses to be late as we expect the addition of the material delivery to extend our route stop timing. 
Starting Thursday, March 19, 2020; please use this link to access the Elementary Remote Learning Materials Online. 
Click here to go to www.mansd.org for the Bus Route Schedules. 


 
March 16, 2020 Update (*Updated March 18, 2020) 
Dear Families of the Manchester School District,
As you are aware MSD buildings closed starting Mon. 3/16/2020, and will remain closed to students until at least Friday 4/3/2020. As we enter this phase of the roll-out of our Remote Learning plan our educators are at school planning and preparing for a positive transition to Remote Learning. Tonight, we wanted to take some time to share important information with you. Two aspects of our Remote Learning plan are Food Distribution and Materials for Remote Learning.
Food Distribution - Beginning March 17th our buses will be used to provide breakfast and lunch for our students. It is not required that students pick up either breakfast or lunch; however, we want to make sure all of our students have access to healthy meals when they are away from our schools. Families received information regarding food distribution via School Messenger. Also, the routes are currently posted on the school district website along with other closure information. We want to remind you to store perishable items in the refrigerator immediately. If you have any questions related to meals please contact your school via phone or email. 
Materials for Remote Learning - Remote learning will begin in a staggered rollout (initial date to be announced). Our instructional teams have been meeting to frame out a remote learning plan for our district for some time now. Since last Friday when Governor Sununu declared NH in a state of emergency due to the coronavirus pandemic, we expanded our team to include a broader range of stakeholders so remote learning can move from plan to implementation for our 13,702 students. We will communicate plans to transition instruction from classrooms and buildings to an at-home learning model in line with our district’s mission “in partnership with the community, to inspire and empower all learners with the knowledge, skills, and experiences essential for them to reach their greatest potential:” 
Managing Remote Learning in the Home - What will this look like for students? We will be sending various communications and updates from the district level, school level and most important, teacher level. We want to ensure that our students and teachers stay connected on a daily basis and the learning opportunities that students have engaged in this school year continue throughout the remote learning process. 
Here are some of the major factors to be aware of:
The students will be provided with a suggested daily schedule.
The teachers will design/provide lessons and activities for learning.
The teachers will assess student work for the development of skills, mastery of competency, or fulfillment of course credit depending on the grade level.

DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":8310,"s":"The students will complete the work by the timeline the teacher has given the student to receive full credit for assignments.
The teachers will be available via email, Google classroom, or other specified platforms to assist students in learning and answer questions relevant to the learning.
Attendance will be recorded daily as this is not a school vacation nor a “snow day”. Teachers will be contacting students and families each day. It is important to respond to the call, email by teachers or show attendance through evidence of presence during any online lessons. 
Families are asked to support our students by encouraging them to reach their daily learning goals and to reach out to teachers when they need help. 
Special Education and 504 and Remote Learning- What will this look like for students? The Manchester School District (local educational agency; LEA) has sought guidance and direction from the Council of Administrators of Special Education (CASE), the US Department of Education, the Office of Special Education and Rehabilitation Services (OSERS) and the Office of Special Education Program (OSEP) to address questions about the provision of services to children with disabilities in accordance with the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) and Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 (Section 504). 
As the district moves to the phase of remote learning, the goal is to allow ALL students continued access to learning opportunities. The District has initiated plans to ensure that students with disabilities are provided a free and appropriate education (FAPE) in accordance with IDEA and Section 504.
Will my child receive a FAPE in accordance with the IEP or Section 504 plan?
Special education staff and therapists will offer a continuum of services based on individual needs of students.
 Service delivery may include but not be limited to remote learning, instructional work packets, instructional telephone calls or video conferencing with students or consults to caregivers, s and other curriculum-based instructional activities and resources. 
Individual and small group therapy sessions may be offered and delivered to students in their schools.
Talking with your student - You know your children best. Let their questions be your guide as to how much information to provide. However, don’t avoid giving them the information that health experts identify as critical to ensuring your children’s health. Be patient; children and youth do not always talk about their concerns readily. Watch for clues that they may want to talk, such as hovering around while you do the dishes or yard work. It is very typical for younger children to ask a few questions, return to playing, then come back to ask more questions. 
When sharing information, it is important to make sure to provide facts without promoting a high level of stress, remind children that adults are working to address this concern, and give children actions they can take to protect themselves. 
Here are a couple of resources from the Child Mind Institute and National Association of School Psychologists to help you engage in conversations with your child about the Coronavirus. https://childmind.org/article/talking-to-kids-about-the-coronavirus/ and (from the National Association of School Psychologists)
Keeping Communication Open in the Days Ahead - In efforts to keep communication open in the days ahead, we ask that you email your student’s school with any changes to phone numbers or email addresses. 
Thank you to all our families for supporting the MSD.
*Translation Services are currently unavailable from our notification provider. Once they become available, we will share this message through email. 
 

Update March 16, 2020
On Sunday night we sent an email with a schedule for medication pickups – please see the following clarification. Only students who have medications that they receive daily from the school nurse should report to school for medication pickup. Update March 15, 2020
Medication and Personal Belongings Pick-Up Schedule

We will facilitate medication pick-ups with the assistance of our school nurses starting on Monday 3/16 - please review the pick-up schedule below.

Starting Tuesday 3/17, we will include facilitation of personal belongings pick-ups with the assistance of our school teams. Students DO NOT need to come to the school to remove all of their personal belongings. We are extending this pick-up option in the event a student would like to retrieve an item of importance to them (examples - instrument, jacket, books, school materials).

Albanian March 14, 2020
Mirembrema,
Ne kemi marrë vendim që të mbyllim Shkollat Publike të Mançesterit duke filluar nga e hëna. Duke filluar nga e marta, ne do të fillojmë planin tonë të mësimit në distancë, i cili përfshin mësimdhënien në internet dhe në bazë të letrës. Do të qëndrojmë nën këtë plan mësimi në distancë për dy javë, të paktën më 27 Mars. Ndërsa i afrohemi asaj date, do të vlerësojmë më tej.
Qëllimi ynë ishte t'i mbajmë shkollat të hapura sa më shumë që të jetë e mundur për të vazhduar t'i shërbejmë plotësisht komunitetit tonë shkollor. Sidoqoftë, lajmet për transmetimin e parë të komunitetit në New Hampshire me të drejtë kanë ngritur shqetësime për shpejtimin e përhapjes së virusit.
Ne jemi duke u përgatitur për këtë mundësi dhe stafi i shkollës është duke punuar shumë për të koordinuar shpërndarjen e ushqimit dhe materialeve mësimore. Prindërit dhe kujdestarët mund të presin komunikim të mëtejshëm në lidhje me këto plane deri të hënën në mëngjes. Për momentin, nëse keni pyetje specifike, ju kërkojmë t'i dërgoni ato në adresën tonë të dedikuar të postës elektronike - covid19@mansd.org .
Faleminderit,
Dr. John Goldhardt

كان هدفنا هو إبقاء المدارس مفتوحة لأطول فترة ممكنة لمواصلة خدمة مجتمع مدرستنا بشكل كامل. ومع ذلك ، فقد أثارت أنباء أول انتقال للمجتمع في نيو هامبشير مخاوف من تسريع انتشار الفيروس.
لقد كنا نستعد لهذا الاحتمال ويعمل موظفو المنطقة التعليمية بجد لتنسيق توزيع المواد الغذائية والمواد التعليمية. يمكن للوالدين والأوصياء توقع مزيد من التواصل بشأن هذه الخطط صباح يوم الاثنين. في الوقت الحالي ، إذا كانت لديك أسئلة محددة ، فإننا نطلب منك إرسالها إلى عنوان بريدنا الإلكتروني المخصص - covid19@mansd.org .

French March 14, 2020 
Bonne après-midi,
Nous avons décidé de fermer les écoles publiques de Manchester à partir de lundi. À partir de mardi, nous commencerons notre plan d'apprentissage à distance, qui comprend un enseignement en ligne et sur papier. Nous resterons dans le cadre de ce plan d'apprentissage à distance pendant deux semaines, jusqu'au 27 mars au moins. À l'approche de cette date, nous procéderons à une évaluation plus approfondie.
Notre objectif était de garder les écoles ouvertes aussi longtemps que possible pour continuer à servir pleinement notre communauté scolaire. Cependant, la nouvelle de la première transmission communautaire dans le New Hampshire a soulevé à juste titre des inquiétudes quant à l'accélération de la propagation du virus.
Nous nous sommes préparés à cette possibilité et le personnel du district scolaire travaille dur pour coordonner la distribution de nourriture et de matériel d'apprentissage. Les parents et les tuteurs peuvent s'attendre à de nouvelles communications sur ces plans d'ici lundi matin. Pour le moment, si vous avez des questions spécifiques, nous vous demandons de les envoyer à notre adresse e-mail dédiée - covid19@mansd.org .
Merci,
Dr. John Goldhardt
Surintendant des écoles










Haitian March 14, 2020 
Bon apremidi,
Nou te pran desizyon pou fèmen Lekòl Piblik Manchester yo kòmanse Lendi. Kòmanse Madi, nou pral kòmanse plan aprantisaj aleka nou an, ki gen ladan tou de ansèyman sou entènèt ak papye ki baze sou. Nou pral rete anba sa a plan aprantisaj aleka pou de semèn, nan omwen Mas 27. Kòm nou apwoche dat sa a, nou pral evalye pi lwen.
Objektif nou se te kenbe lekòl ouvè osi lontan ke posib pou kontinye sèvi konplètman kominote lekòl nou an. Sepandan, nouvèl nan transmisyon kominote an premye nan New Hampshire just te leve enkyetid sou vitès gaye nan viris la.
Nou te prepare pou posibilite sa a epi anplwaye distri lekòl la ap travay di pou kowòdone distribisyon manje ak materyèl pou aprann. Paran yo ak gadyen yo ka atann plis kominikasyon sou plan sa yo pa Lendi maten. Pou moman sa a, si ou gen kesyon espesifik, nou mande ke ou voye yo nan adrès imèl dedye nou an - covid19@mansd.org .
Mèsi,
Doktè John Goldhardt
Sipèentandan lekòl yo












Portuguese March 14, 2020
Boa tarde,
Decidimos encerrar as escolas públicas de Manchester a partir de segunda-feira. A partir de terça-feira, iniciaremos nosso plano de aprendizado remoto, que inclui ensino on-line e em papel. Permaneceremos sob esse plano de aprendizado remoto por duas semanas, até pelo menos 27 de março. À medida que nos aproximamos dessa data, avaliaremos mais.
Nosso objetivo era manter as escolas abertas o maior tempo possível para continuar a servir plenamente nossa comunidade escolar. No entanto, as notícias da primeira transmissão comunitária em New Hampshire levantaram, com razão, preocupações de acelerar a propagação do vírus.
Estamos nos preparando para essa possibilidade e os funcionários do distrito escolar estão trabalhando duro para coordenar a distribuição de alimentos e materiais de aprendizagem. Os pais e responsáveis podem esperar mais comunicação sobre esses planos até segunda-feira de manhã. No momento, se você tiver perguntas específicas, solicitamos que você as envie para o nosso endereço de e-mail dedicado - covid19@mansd.org .
Obrigado,
Dr. John Goldhardt
Superintendente de Escolas











Spanish March 14, 2020 
Buenas tardes,
Tomamos la decisión de cerrar las Escuelas Públicas de Manchester a partir del lunes. A partir del martes, comenzaremos nuestro plan de aprendizaje remoto, que incluye enseñanza en línea y en papel. Permaneceremos bajo este plan de aprendizaje remoto durante dos semanas, al menos hasta el 27 de marzo. A medida que nos acercamos a esa fecha, realizaremos más evaluaciones.
Nuestro objetivo era mantener las escuelas abiertas el mayor tiempo posible para continuar sirviendo completamente a nuestra comunidad escolar. Sin embargo, la noticia de la primera transmisión comunitaria en New Hampshire ha generado legítimamente preocupaciones de acelerar la propagación del virus.

Mchana mzuri,
Tumefanya uamuzi wa kufunga Shule za Umma za Manchester kuanzia Jumatatu. Kuanzia Jumanne, tutaanza mpango wetu wa kujifunza kijijini, ambao unajumuisha kufundisha mkondoni na kwa karatasi. Tutabaki chini ya mpango huu wa kijijini wa kujifunza kwa muda wa wiki mbili, hadi angalau Machi 27. Tunakaribia tarehe hiyo, tutakagua zaidi.
Kusudi letu lilikuwa kuweka shule zikiwa wazi kwa muda mrefu iwezekanavyo ili kuendelea kuhudumia jamii yetu ya shule kikamilifu. Walakini, habari ya maambukizi ya jamii ya kwanza huko New Hampshire imeibua kwa usawa wasiwasi wa kuharakisha kuenea kwa virusi.
Tumekuwa tukijiandaa kwa uwezekano huu na wafanyikazi wa wilaya ya shule wanafanya bidii kuratibu usambazaji wa vifaa vya chakula na vifaa vya kujifunzia. Wazazi na walezi wanaweza kutarajia mawasiliano zaidi juu ya mipango hii ifikapo Jumatatu asubuhi. Kwa sasa, ikiwa una maswali maalum, tunaomba uwatume kwa anwani yetu ya barua pepe iliyojitolea - covid19@mansd.org .
Asante,
Dk. John Goldhardt

Vietnamese March 14, 2020 
Chào buổi trưa,
Chúng tôi đã đưa ra quyết định đóng cửa các trường công lập Manchester bắt đầu từ thứ Hai. Bắt đầu từ thứ ba, chúng tôi sẽ bắt đầu kế hoạch học tập từ xa, bao gồm cả giảng dạy trực tuyến và trên giấy. Chúng tôi sẽ ở lại trong kế hoạch học tập từ xa này trong hai tuần, ít nhất là vào ngày 27 tháng 3. Khi chúng tôi đến ngày đó, chúng tôi sẽ đánh giá thêm.
Mục tiêu của chúng tôi là giữ cho các trường mở càng lâu càng tốt để tiếp tục phục vụ đầy đủ cho cộng đồng trường học của chúng tôi. Tuy nhiên, tin tức về sự lây truyền cộng đồng đầu tiên ở New Hampshire đã làm dấy lên mối lo ngại về việc tăng tốc độ lây lan của virus.
Chúng tôi đã chuẩn bị cho khả năng này và nhân viên khu học chánh đang nỗ lực để phối hợp phân phối thực phẩm và học liệu. Phụ huynh và người giám hộ có thể mong đợi thông tin liên lạc về các kế hoạch này vào sáng thứ Hai. Hiện tại, nếu bạn có câu hỏi cụ thể, chúng tôi yêu cầu bạn gửi chúng đến địa chỉ email chuyên dụng của chúng tôi - covid19@mansd.org .
Cảm ơn bạn,
Tiến sĩ John Goldhardt

March 13, 2020
Good Evening,
We’re sending this update to provide you with the latest information on our response to COVID-19. 
School is open: Manchester Public Schools remain open. We are currently following our Emergency Operations Plan, and we are working closely with the city Health Department and New Hampshire state officials to ensure the safety and well being of students, staff, and families. As part of our Emergency Operations Plan, we are preparing for the possibility of an extended school closure, however nothing is imminent. 
If you choose to keep your child home: We understand that you may not want to send your child to school – our recommendation is to communicate with the school principal if you choose to keep your child home so that you can coordinate plans. 
Cancellations: All international and out of state trips are being canceled or postponed, while other field trips are being reviewed on a case-by-case basis. Similarly, school events are being reviewed on a case-by-case basis. Our athletic director is working with our athletic affiliations including the NHIAA to determine plans for Spring sporting events. All NHIAA tournaments have been canceled.
Cleaning: We are currently following standard cleaning procedures in school facilities, and our custodial services provider is prepared to implement an elevated response in consultation with the Health Department and school district.

March 6, 2020
The Manchester School District is continuing to work with community partners and the state in response to Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19). Since COVID-19 is very new, information about the virus is continually developing. We will continue to send district-wide messages when we have new information.
Today, we wanted to provide a few quick updates on what we’ve been doing and reminders on what members of our school community are being asked to do:
What we are doing
Actively participating with the Emergency Operations Center: We’re working with numerous city departments as well as Catholic Medical Center, Elliot Hospital and AMR to coordinate planning and response.
Working with contractors on cleaning: We are in close contact with Aramark, which provides cleaning services for our schools, and we are prepared for enhanced cleaning procedures if the need arises. In addition, we’re working with Manchester Transit Authority and special transportation partners about procedures for cleaning student transportation. 
Setting up hand sanitizing stations: Thanks to a donation by Catholic Medical Center, we will be installing hand sanitizer dispensers in the lobbies of all schools. 
What members of the school community are asked to do
Wash your hands and cover your cough: These are the most basic prevention measures for COVID-19, as well as the flu. 
If you’ve traveled to Italy, South Korea, China, Iran or Japan, stay home: The Centers for Disease Control recommends anyone who has travelled to these countries stay home from school for 14 days from the date you returned to the U.S.
You can find information on COVID-19 response and prevention efforts here in New Hampshire at https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/dphs/cdcs/2019-ncov.htm. 







March 4, 2020

Dear Manchester Families & Staff ~
 We apologize for this late notice however, we have been working with the Manchester Health Department into the evening in order to provide you with the most current and accurate guidance related to COVID-19. 
 The Manchester School District learned from its partners at the State of New Hampshire and Manchester Health Departments that THE CDC has changed their recommendation regarding those who traveled to Italy and other countries. Click https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices for their latest travel advisory.
 "After consulting with our health partners, and out of an abundance of caution, we are requesting all staff members and students who have traveled to Italy, South Korea, China, Iran or Japan to self- quarantine and STAY HOME from school as recommended by the CDC. This is effective immediately."
 The recommendation is to STAY HOME for 14 days from the day that you returned to the United States.

Të nderuar Familje dhe Stafi të Mançesterit ~
Sidoqoftë, ju kërkojmë falje për këtë njoftim të vonë, ne kemi qenë duke punuar me Departamentin e Shëndetit në Manchester, në mbrëmje, në mënyrë që t'ju ofrojmë udhëzimet më aktuale dhe të sakta në lidhje me COVID-19.
Qarku i Shkollave të Mançesterit mësoi nga partnerët e tij në Shtetin e New Hampshire dhe Departamentet e Shëndetit të Mançesterit se CDC ka ndryshuar rekomandimin e tyre në lidhje me ata që udhëtuan në Itali dhe vende të tjera. Kliko https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices për këshillat e tyre të fundit të udhëtimit.
"Pas konsultimit me partnerët tanë shëndetësorë, dhe nga një bollëk e kujdes, ne po kërkojmë nga të gjithë anëtarët e stafit dhe studentët që kanë udhëtuar në Itali, Korenë e Jugut, Kinë, Iran ose Japoni për të karantinuar dhe Qëndruar SHTPI nga shkolla siç rekomandohet nga CDC. Kjo është efektive menjëherë ".
Rekomandimi është të qëndroni në shtëpi për 14 ditë nga dita kur u kthyet në Shtetet e Bashkuara.
Kliko KETU për Udhëzuesin e Vëzhgimit të Vetë
Nëse keni ndonjë pyetje në lidhje me këtë njoftim, ju lutemi kontaktoni infermierin e shkollës së fëmijës tuaj ose Degën e Sëmundjeve Infektive të Departamentit të Shëndetit të Mançesterit në 624-6466. Qarku i Shkollave në Manchester do të jetë fleksibël gjatë kësaj mungese të justifikuar.
sinqerisht,
Dr. John Goldhardt

عزيزي مانشستر العائلات والموظفين ~
نعتذر عن هذا الإشعار المتأخر ، ومع ذلك ، فإننا نعمل مع إدارة صحة مانشستر حتى المساء لنوفر لك أحدث التوجيهات الأكثر دقة ودقة فيما يتعلق بـ COVID-19.
علمت منطقة مدارس مانشستر من شركائها في إدارتي ولاية نيو هامبشاير ومانشستر للصحة أن مركز السيطرة على الأمراض قد غير توصيتهم فيما يتعلق بأولئك الذين سافروا إلى إيطاليا ودول أخرى. انقر https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices للحصول على أحدث نصائح السفر الخاصة بهم.
"بعد التشاور مع شركائنا الصحيين ، وبدون وفرة من الحذر ، نطلب من جميع أعضاء هيئة التدريس والطلاب الذين سافروا إلى إيطاليا أو كوريا الجنوبية أو الصين أو إيران أو اليابان أن يفرضوا الحجر الصحي وأن يبقىوا في المنزل من المدرسة على النحو الموصى به من قبل CDC. هذا فعال على الفور. "
التوصية هي البقاء في المنزل لمدة 14 يومًا من يوم عودتك إلى الولايات المتحدة.
انقر هنا لدليل المراقبة الذاتية
إذا كانت لديك أي أسئلة بخصوص هذا الإشعار ، فيرجى الاتصال بممرضة مدرسة طفلك أو فرع الأمراض المعدية التابع لإدارة الصحة في مانشستر على الرقم 624-6466. ستكون مدرسة Manchester School District مرنة خلال هذا الغياب العذر
بإخلاص،
الدكتور جون جولدهاردت
مدير مدرسة مقاطعة مانشست

Cela prend effet immédiatement. "

4 de marzo de 2020
 
Estimadas familias y personal de Manchester ~
Sin embargo, nos disculpamos por esta notificación tardía, hemos estado trabajando con el Departamento de Salud de Manchester hasta la noche para brindarle la orientación más actualizada y precisa relacionada con COVID-19.
El Distrito Escolar de Manchester aprendió de sus socios en los Departamentos de Salud del Estado de New Hampshire y Manchester que THE CDC ha cambiado su recomendación con respecto a aquellos que viajaron a Italia y otros países. Hacer clic https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices para su último aviso de viaje.
"Después de consultar con nuestros socios de salud, y por precaución, estamos solicitando a todos los miembros del personal y estudiantes que han viajado a Italia, Corea del Sur, China, Irán o Japón que se sometan a cuarentena y se QUEDEN EN CASA desde la escuela, según lo recomendado por los CDC. Esto es efectivo de inmediato ".
La recomendación es QUEDARSE EN CASA durante 14 días a partir del día en que regresó a los Estados Unidos.
Hacer clic AQUÍ para la Guía de auto observación
Si tiene alguna pregunta sobre este aviso, comuníquese con la enfermera de la escuela de su hijo o la División de Enfermedades Infecciosas del Departamento de Salud de Manchester al 624-6466. El Distrito Escolar de Manchester será flexible durante esta ausencia justificada.
Sinceramente,
Dr. John Goldhardt
Superintendente del Distrito Escolar de Manchester




Vietnamese 

Ngày 4 tháng 3 năm 2020
 
Kính gửi các gia đình và nhân viên Manchester ~
Chúng tôi xin lỗi vì thông báo muộn này, tuy nhiên, chúng tôi đã làm việc với Sở Y tế Manchester vào buổi tối để cung cấp cho bạn hướng dẫn chính xác và mới nhất liên quan đến COVID-19.
Học Khu Manchester đã học được từ các đối tác của mình tại Bộ Y tế Bang New Hampshire và Manchester rằng CDC đã thay đổi khuyến nghị của họ về những người đi du lịch đến Ý và các quốc gia khác. Nhấp chuột https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices cho lời khuyên du lịch mới nhất của họ.
"Sau khi tham khảo ý kiến với các đối tác y tế của chúng tôi và hết sức thận trọng, chúng tôi đang yêu cầu tất cả các nhân viên và học sinh đã đến Ý, Hàn Quốc, Trung Quốc, Iran hoặc Nhật Bản để tự cách ly và TẠO NHÀ khỏi trường theo khuyến nghị của CDC. Điều này có hiệu lực ngay lập tức. "
Lời khuyên là hãy TRỞ LẠI NHÀ trong 14 ngày kể từ ngày bạn trở về Hoa Kỳ.
Nhấp chuột ĐÂY cho Hướng dẫn tự quan sát
Nếu bạn có bất kỳ câu hỏi nào liên quan đến thông báo này, xin vui lòng liên hệ với y tá trường học của con bạn hoặc Chi nhánh Bệnh truyền nhiễm của Sở Y tế Manchester theo số 624-6466. Học Khu Manchester sẽ linh hoạt trong thời gian vắng mặt này.
Trân trọng,
Tiến sĩ John Goldhardt
Giám thị khu học chánh Manchester



March 1, 2020 
Dear Parents and Guardians,
We are writing to provide you an update about Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19). There have been no cases of COVID-19 yet identified in New Hampshire; however, it is important for all of us to make sure we are taking precautions to help prevent the spread of COVID-19 and other respiratory illness, such as the flu, which we frequently see this time of year.
COVID-19 and many other common respiratory viruses spread through contact with an infected person’s respiratory droplets, such as when a person coughs or sneezes. To prevent the spread of respiratory viruses, the CDC recommends that individuals engage in everyday preventive measures to help stop the spread of germs and avoid illness, such as:
Teach your children to wash their hands. Wash hands frequently with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use alcohol-based hand sanitizers.

DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":37681,"s":"Teach your children to cover a cough or sneeze with a tissue, then immediately discard the tissue in the trash. It is also recommended to cough or sneeze into their elbow if a tissue is not available. 
Teach your children to avoid touching eyes, mouth and nose with unwashed hands.
Avoid close contact with individuals who are sick.
Keep sick children at home. Children should stay at home for at least 24 hours after the last signs of a fever without the use of fever-reducing medicine. Those who have a constant cough should stay home until medicine relieves it. Any child that is sick at school should go home.
Report your child’s absence to the nurse. If your child is out sick with illness, please let the nurse know.
Teach your child not to share personal items like their food or water bottles.
Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces within your home.
In addition to these personal prevention measures, our school families should avoid all travel to any locations for which CDC has issued a Level 3 travel notice: https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices. Travel to other countries outside of the U.S. should be discussed with the family’s healthcare provider.
According to the health department, people who have returned from mainland China are being monitored by public health authorities and must stay home for 14 days after their travel. People who have returned from other locations with travel notices for COVID-19 may continue to attend work and school. Travelers that develop symptoms (e.g. fever, cough, or shortness of breath), should:
Take their temperature with a thermometer.
Stay home and avoid close contact with other people.
Seek health advice by phone from either a healthcare provider or the NH Division of Public Health Services at 603-271-4496 (after-hours: 603-271-5300).
Before going to a doctor’s office or emergency room, call ahead and tell the provider or office about recent travel and symptoms.
Practice strict respiratory etiquette and hand hygiene including covering the nose and mouth with a tissue when coughing or sneezing and washing hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds, or using an alcohol-based hand sanitizer if soap and water are not available.
If available, wear a surgical mask when traveling outside of the home (e.g. to a doctor’s office)
Outbreaks involving COVID-19 evolve quickly and recommendations from public health officials may change as new information becomes available. Please check the following websites often for updated information:
U.S. CDC website: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019ncov/summary.html
NH Division of Public Health Services website: https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/dphs/cdcs/2019-ncov.htm
Sincerely,
Dr. John Goldhardt, Superintendent, Manchester School District
